<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 Congress read this letter on 9 Feb. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:123). Internal evidence indicates that the latter part of this letter was written on 31 Jan. (see note 22).</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>For Congresss request for reinforcements for Canada, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0104" class="document">Hancock to GW, 20 Jan. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0026&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0001#GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0001" class="document">Hancock to GW, 621 Jan. 1776, n.1</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0158" class="document">GW to William Howe, this date</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>This sentence is in GWs writing. Hancock requested GWs opinion on this subject in his letter of 621 January. A report submitted to Congress in February suggested that GWs aides rank as majors, but on 5 June 1776 Congress resolved that they be lieutenant colonels (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:155, 5:418).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>The unnamed gentleman was Midshipman John Atkinson who was captured by the Americans on 17 December. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0568" class="document">GW to Richard Henry Lee, 26 Dec. 1775</a>. For the efforts to find Connollys hidden instructions, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0026&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0003#GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0003" class="document">Hancock to GW, 621 Jan. 1776, n.3</a>, and note 21 below.</p>

</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0220">[220]</span>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>In arranging the army for 1776, GW reserved places for those officers who had gone to Quebec with Arnold. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0260" class="document">Council of War, 2 Nov. 1775</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0444" class="document">GW to Arnold, 5 Dec. 1775</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0049" class="document">12 Jan. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0026&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0010#GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0010" class="document">Hancock to GW, 621 Jan. 1776, n.10</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>The words &amp; waste, in spite of all the care in the world are inserted above the line in GWs writing.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>The words Independant of their Stores are inserted above the line in GWs writing.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0009">9</a>

   <p>The word Stores is inserted at the end of a line in GWs writing.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0010-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0010">10</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0026&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0008#GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0008" class="document">Hancock to GW, 621 Jan. 1776, n.8</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0011-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0011">11</a>

   <p>For the dispute over the status of these independent companies, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0026&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0013#GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0013" class="document">Hancock to GW, 621 Jan. 1776, n.13</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0012-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0012">12</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0077&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0077-fn-0001#GEWN-03-03-02-0077-fn-0001" class="document">Thomas Lynch to GW, 16 Jan. 1776, n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0013-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0013">13</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0094" class="document">Hancock to GW, 18 Jan. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0014-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0014">14</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0104" class="document">Hancock to GW, 20 Jan. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0015-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0015">15</a>

   <p>The words of Grenadiers &amp; light Infantry are inserted above the line in GWs writing. For Henry Clintons southern expedition, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0122&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0008#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0008" class="document">GW to Charles Lee, 23 Jan. 1776, n.8</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0016-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0016">16</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0145" class="document">GW to Schuyler, 27 Jan. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0017-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0017">17</a>

   <p>For Robert Cochrans mission to recruit seamen in New England for South Carolinas naval forces, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0104&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0104-fn-0009#GEWN-03-03-02-0104-fn-0009" class="document">Hancock to GW, 20 Jan. 1776, n.9</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0018-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0018">18</a>

   <p>For John Manleys capture of the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Happy Return</span> and the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Norfolk</span> on 25 Jan., see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0138&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0138-fn-0001#GEWN-03-03-02-0138-fn-0001" class="document">William Watson to GW, 26 Jan. 1776, n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0019-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0019">19</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0104" class="document">Hancock to GW, 20 Jan. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0020-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0020">20</a>

   <p>See note 4.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0021-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0021">21</a>
	
   <p>Connollys servant destroyed these pillion sticks before their contents could be discovered. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0026&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0003#GEWN-03-03-02-0026-fn-0003" class="document">Hancock to GW, 621 <span class="choice correction" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Corrected from 'June' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2007-02-25]]&lt;/span&gt; ]">Jan.</span> 1776, n.3</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0022-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0022">22</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0161" class="document">Speeches of the Caughnawaga, St. Johns, and Passamaquoddy Indians, 31 Jan. 1776</a>. The date of this enclosure indicates that this paragraph and the following one were written on 31 January.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0023-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0023">23</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0173" class="document">GW to Schuyler, 1 Feb. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0024-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0024">24</a>
	
   <p>GW sent Aaron Willard and Moses Child to Nova Scotia. See his <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0388" class="document">instructions to Willard and Child</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0386" class="document">GW to a Committee of the Massachusetts Council</a>, both 24 Nov. 1775. For GWs statement on the insufficiency of his force for an expedition to Nova Scotia, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0404" class="document">GW to Hancock, 28 Nov. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0025-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0025">25</a>

   <p>The plan that Samuel Thompson and Jeremiah OBrien presented to GW reads: For the Expedition purposd one Thousand Men Including Officers four Armd Vessels &amp; Eight Transports The Men to Be Raisd at the Eastward The Fleet to Be Made up at Mechias &amp; Then Proceed to Winsor Captivate the Torys Make all The Prosfolites [proselytes] wee Can &amp; Then Proceed to halifax If Possable destroy the Kings Dock Yard &amp; Town If Thought Proper. It May Be undertaken for five Thousand Pound Lw. [lawful money] and all That Can Be procurd from the Torys or Ten Thousand &amp; the one half of what Is Taken from Them at winsor we understand There is abundance of Good[s] which is the Next Capital town to halifax we are Lately Informd That There is Not to Exceed 200 Brittish Troop[s] in halifax (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>; see also copy, in Stephen Moylans writing, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Papers of the Continental Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA:PCC</span>, item 152). Samuel Thompson
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0221">[221]</span>
(17351798), a prominent innkeeper and land speculator, represented Brunswick, Maine, in the three Massachusetts provincial congresses from 1774 to 1775 and in the General Court from 1775 to 1777. Thompson became a colonel in the Cumberland County militia early in 1775 and was commissioned a brigadier general of the militia on 8 Feb. 1776.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0026-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0026">26</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy includes here the words from the Continent.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0027-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0157-fn-0027">27</a>

   <p>On 16 Feb. a committee of the Congress reported, that Congress submit the expediancy and practicability of an Expedition to Nova Scotia, to Genl Washington, and would by no means accept the plan proposed by Thompson and Obrian so far as relates to Tory Property nor the destruction of the Town of Halifax (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:155). Congress apparently did not act on this report, and GW received no instructions on the matter.</p>

</div>
